node.text:
I don’t battle food anymore. I did, for years I did. 

But now, in this house, in this body, we don’t play that game. 

A huge shift occurred for me when I stopped seeing FOOD as the enemy,

And started looking at it as FUEL. 

Fuel for my body, 
To help drive towards any goals I have:
Run faster. Lift heavier. 
Feel stronger. 

But also fuel for my soul. 

Sometimes that means eating grandma’s cake. 
Or having a cookie baked by a love one. 
Or diving in to a plate of pasta, made by a man you’re about to marry. 

And that’s wonderful too. 

So today, I just want to gently remind you:
Your body is not a battle ground,
And eating isn’t the enemy. 

You deserve to feel nourished,
Both in your body,
And in your soul. 

x

Kit @womensbest @womensbestwear 

#womensbestathlete #bodyconfidence #selflove #bodyacceptance

I intended this to be a light-hearted post. A playful, tongue-in-cheek skit looking at introverts and parties. 

But the post had other ideas. 

To this day, I’m still a little self conscious about being an introvert. 
I feel shy that I DON’T like parties, that I never really have.
I’m embarrassed that giant crowds, thumping night clubs, those aren’t my idea of fun. 

I struggle with it, in my own little, soft way. 

And I figure if I’m still learning to navigate being introverted in an extroverted world, 
Or even being true to myself, in a world that tries to tell us otherwise,
Maybe you are too.

So today, I want to remind me and you and us:

It is ok to lean into what ACTUALLY brings you joy,
And pull away from things that don’t. 

You do not HAVE to go to that frat party,
Or that loud club,
Or that event full of people which will leave you feeling empty. 

It is absolutely fine to slide into quiet spaces: 
Bookstores, cafes, mornings on the beach with the closest of friends. 

Or just to find your people where YOU yourself like to be. 

For me, that has been at the gym, in sports, and in art. 
For you, that might be a dozen other places. And that’s ok. 

Wherever you go, make sure you go in a way that is TRUE to you. 

You don’t have to change a thing about yourself. 
Just change the things around you. 

Because life is too short to hide in bathrooms,
And you — introverted or extroverted, noisy or loud, passionate or shy — are glorious just the way you are.

x

#introverts #selflove #bodyconfidence #introverted

This app edits BODIES in VIDEOS - and trust me, technology like this is only becoming more common. 

In a matter of seconds, I was able to:
Enhance my bust
Get a bigger bum 
Lift my thighs 
Shrink my tummy 
And so much more. 

If I wanted to, I could have also made my legs longer, filtered my face and done a dozen other things. 

And it was SO EASY to do. 

Technology like this is popping up more and more. It’s all the big screen Hollywood tools, brought to your phone. 

And it’s constantly getting SMARTER. Like this app includes an option to BLUR the background, so that you don’t see WHERE the edits have happened. 

So please, the next time you start to compare yourself to what you see on here, remember that the INTERNET is CURATED. 
Filtered. 
Posed. 
Aaaand sometimes even assisted with a body photoshopping video app. 

In other words, your offline self doing great.

node.text:
There will always be someone who cannot see your worth. 

Just make sure that person is not you. 

Because you, my dear,
You are enough. 

You always have been. 

Even if your energy is not theirs. 
Even if your body comes in a different shape,
Or your smile in its own form. 

These things don’t make you less than. 
They don’t mean you’re lacking. 

They’re just parts and pieces 
Of the marvel, the magic that you are. 

And if they cannot see it, 
That is ok;
People all vibrate to their own rhythm. 

But it doesn’t mean you have to listen. 

The voice that matters is your own. 

So today and tomorrow and every day,
Remind yourself:
You, you glorious complex creature,
You marvellous woman,
However you choose to show up, however you choose to be you,
You are enough. 

You. Are. Enough. 

x

#selflove #bodyconfidence #bodyacceptance #positivequotes

I can’t wait to be back home. 

Three years ago, I wouldn’t have really understood this sentiment. 

Home was never something I had growing up. 
And as an adult, as a travel journalist living around the world, it never really came into play. 

But when I adopted Kiki cat, things started to change. 
With Koala kitten, they shifted even more. 
They brought peace. Laughter. 
A reason to feel impatient getting back to that front door. 

And now there’s him:
The voice on the other end of the line. 
The messages sent down a phone. 
‘What are you doing now?’ And ‘what did you eat today?’ And ‘make sure you don’t leave the kitties alone.’ 

Somewhere between the first four paws and this Italian fiancée, a piece inside me changed. 

House became home. 
And I can’t wait to get back to mine. 

x

node.text:
Posed vs Relaxed / Or let’s talk TEENAGE BOYS and GROWN MEN.

Some of the harshest hate I get is from teenage boys.
Some of the most ardent shouts of ‘FAKE! Bodies don’t look like THAT and also THAT’ are from grown men. 

And when they aren’t critiquing,
They’re sliding and slipping into my DMs.
With words, with language, I won’t repeat here. 

Right now we have teenage boys making videos mocking bodies, 
And grown men in comment sections doing the same. 

We have young girls learning that in order to be LOVED,
They must be POSED. Perfected. GLOSSY. 
And grown women desperately 
Trying to unlearn the same. 

So how do we change it? 

I don’t have the full answer.
But I do know this: 
It starts with us. 
It starts in our HOMES and in our LIVES.
And here. On our SOCIAL MEDIA FEEDS. 
Where we show who WE ARE. 
In ALL our ways. 
Our shiny, sparkly, well-lit, filtered, glorious selves,
And our wobbly, delicate, raw, tumbling, human ones too. 

We do this bit by bit, 
Day by day. 
Changing the conversation word by truth by word.
For ourselves. 
But also for them. 

For the tomorrows. 

#instavsreality #selflove #bodyconfidence #bodyacceptance

node.text:
I went to a fertility clinic today. 

I wanted to understand what was happening inside my body. Were my eggs healthy? Was I healthy? Could I create a child, hold it, grow it? 

Could I become a mom? 

And so @bournhallfertilityclinicuae did some tests. 
They sat me down with Dr. Diana. 
They talked to me. 

Dr. Diana is the first professional that has ever told me about my eggs. 
She’s the first doctor who explained what was happening inside: age, fertility, timelines. 
She’s the first person who pulled up numbers and walked me through my own charts, my own data. 

I can’t believe this knowledge isn’t more mainstream.

There is so much happening inside us,
And so much critical education is left out. 

My results were good, Dr. Diana said. 
Healthy overall. 
Only my egg reserve was a little lower than she would have liked. 

‘Do not train too hard,’ came the advice. 
Eat. Relax. Avoid stress. 

Honor this body that I exist in, 
So it can create a space where another might grow. 

The advice feels fragile. 
As if I’ve sent a dream out into the world, 
And maybe now, like a wish spoken aloud, 
It might not come true. 

I’d like it to come true. 

And yet, alongside this delicate fear that comes with any growth,
I’m so glad I went.
And that I’m learning, exploring,
Asking questions and setting goals. 

Even though I can’t predict exactly what comes next,
Or control all that happens within.

I can feel empowered by the knowledge all the same, 
And thankful,
So very thankful,
That we are in this journey together. 

x

Photo by @chiclebelle 

#selflove #fertility #pregnancy #femaleempowerment

node.text:
How do influencers FAKE THIGH GAPS? Especially while laying down in those casual home selfies or that chilled bikini pose? 

Let me tell ya:

They hold up wobbly wibbly thigh flesh. 

Like what I’m doing here: 

In my ‘posed’ photo, I am:
- Manually lifting my thigh UP and away from my bottom leg
- Arching my back
- Squeezing my core
- Lifting my legs apart to create even more of a thigh gap
- And ‘casually’ taking the photo.

When I let go? 
My THIGH wobbles again, and even touches the one below. 
Because that’s just what my thighs like to do. :) 

Of course, plenty of influencers actually HAVE thigh gaps. 
And plenty others DON’T. 
Some thighs want lots of thigh kisses. 
Other things prefer to keep their distance. 
And that’s ok, because BODIES are built DIFFERENTLY.

My point here is to stress that SO much of what we see online is CURATED.
There are so many ways to ‘FAKE’ or ‘HACK’ the system to create certain trendy aesthetics. 

So don’t let a single SNAPSHOT 
Make you feel bad about your real, joyful, courageous storybook. 

Get out there and rock that glorious life of yours. 

x

#selflove #instavsreality #socialmediavsreality #onlinevsreality #posingtruths #bodyconfidence
